In this article, President Barack Obama proclaims May 20-26, 2012, as World Trade Week in the United States. He emphasizes the importance of exports in creating jobs and growing the economy. The National Export Initiative, launched by the administration, aims to double exports by the end of 2014. The president highlights the historic progress made, with exports surpassing $2.1 trillion for the first time in history. The signing of three trade agreements with Korea, Panama, and Colombia is mentioned, as they will make it easier for American companies to sell their products and support thousands of jobs. The Interagency Trade Enforcement Center is created to investigate unfair trade practices globally. The president emphasizes the need to look beyond US borders to open new markets for American exporters, and he encourages Americans to observe World Trade Week with events that celebrate and inform about the benefits of trade.